      <h3>Policy on housing development in Sanderstead and surrounding area</h3>
      <p> Whilst embracing the principle that any property owner should be able to develop their own property, Sanderstead Residents Association also follows the principle that any such development should not be at the detriment to neighbours amenity particularly where there is over-looking, loss of daylight or sunlight, out of keeping with its neighbours and if it is to such density as not to provide recreational space either as part of the property development or be within easy access of public spaces.</p>
      <p>For these reasons, Sanderstead Residents Association policy continues to object to ‘back garden’ and multi-occupation developments on property of single dwellings. However, Croydon Council’s current policy is to use every spare piece of land in order to achieve their goal of 1,000 new homes across the borough by 2019 which aligns with The Mayor of London’s announcement on 26th November setting out plans to speed up the building of homes in the capital and new (presumably less onerous for developers) planning guidance to achieve this.</p>
      <p>Recently some residents have been approached by property development companies to purchase property with various incentives to ‘ease the burden’. Whilst each approach should be dealt with on its merits, residents are advised to make careful and considerate enquires, including professional advice if necessary, before entering into negotiations and subsequent contractual arrangements with any such company.</p>
      <p>Remember the old adage ‘if it sounds too good to be true – it probably is’.</p> 
